               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Where are we on a sphere?</h3>In the previous section, we extracted a flat disc from a sphere and learned to position ourselves on it. Now, let’s try a practical exercise:</p><p><center><div class=\"first_steps_lab_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_lab question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-microscope\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_lab\"><b>Creating a Sphere</b><br /><br />Draw a circle on a sheet of paper; you can use a plate as a guide, tracing around it with a pencil. Then, cut out the circle. Place it in front of you horizontally, and spin it a few times toward your feet.</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "By spinning the circle, we representing a sphere, similar to our planet, as shown in the image in this section. This exercise also highlights the need to define an additional variable to locate ourselves beyond a flat disc. This extra variable, represented by the Greek letter phi (<b>ϕ</b>), covers values between 0 and π radians, or 0 to 180 degrees. Introducing Phi (<b>ϕ</b>) transitions us from polar coordinates to spherical coordinates",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "fd003897-89a6-4d01-ae79-da9e564d9583",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
